The RING server ( http://protein.bio.unipd.it/ ring) gives a set of physico-chemically validated amino acid contacts (Martin et al., 2011 ), and imports it to the widely used Cytoscape plat- form ( Smoot et al., 2011 ) enabling their network analysis using the tool-inventory described in Section 2 .
Recently a speci ﬁc, Cytoscape- linked ( Smoot et al., 2011 ) tool-kit for protein structure network assess- ment, RINalyzer ( http://www.rinalyzer.de ) was published.

The pro- gram is complemented by a protein structure determination module, called RINerator ( http://rinalizer.de/rindata.php ), which determines the protein structure networks and stores pre-determined protein structure networks of Protein Data Bank 3D protein structure ﬁles.

The RINalyzer program was also linked to the NetworkAnalyzer soft- ware ( http://med.bioinf.mpi-inf.mpg.de/netanalyzer ;Assenov et al., 2008 ) allowing the comparison of protein structure networks and the extension of their analysis to protein –protein interaction networks (Doncheva et al., 2011, 2012b ).

xPyder provides an interface between the widely employed molecular graphics system, PyMOL and the analysis of dynamical cross-correlation matrices ( http://linux.btbs.unimib.it/ xpyder ;Pasi et al., 2012 ).

The online interface at http://sdb.cns.iu.edu provides access to four datasets: MEDLINE papers, U.S. Patent and Trademark Oce patents (USPTO), National Science Foun- dation (NSF) funding, and National Institutes of Health (NIH) funding { over 25 million records in total.

In interactive interface of dierent researcher networking systems and their data holdings can be found at http://nrn.cns.iu.edu , see Figure 4.

Another example of interest is the Econophysics Forum ( http://unifr.ch/econophysics ) as an example of an online scientic community, sharing dierent kinds of content (papers, reviews, blogs, events, and so on).

Other platforms that facilitate the exchange of scientic (bibliometric) data include Mendeley, iamScientist, MS Academic, and again Google Scholar, with advanced derivatives such as Schol- arometer ( http://scholarometer.indiana.edu ) or Harzing's Publish or Perish ( http://www.

The Cyberinfrastructure Shell (CIShell) ( http://cishell.org ) (Herr II et al., 2007) provides an easy to use, modular, scalable means to integrate and use datasets, algorithms, tools, and comput- ing resources.
It builds upon the Open Services Gateway Initiative (OSGi) ( http://www.osgi.org ) specication, thus leveraging a large amount of industry standard code and know-how.

Today, CIShell is at the core of the major cyberinfrastructures and tools that serve the Information Vi- sualization ( http://iv.cns.iu.edu ), Network Science ( http://nwb.cns.iu.edu ), Science Policy (http://sci2.cns.iu.edu ), and Epidemics research communities.

Sloot at the University of Amsterdam, The Netherlands develops algorithms to study evolving networks; SISOB (http://sisob.lcc.uma.es ) an Observatory for Science in Society Based in Social Models.

From a scientic publication point of view, workows and other computational methods highlight two major innovations: Publishing method: Rather than just publishing the results of method, novel platforms such as QScience ( http://www.qlectives.eu/qscience ), HubZero ( http://hubzero.org ) and myEx- periment ( http://www.myexperiment.org ) enable the social networking and sharing of scientic methods, allow scientists to share and execute scientic workows, or to nd and reuse publicly available workows, in the case of myExperiment, or simulation scripts in the case of HubZero.

We quote from the website of Elseviers 2011 Executable paper challenge ( http://www.executablepapers.com ): "Data sets, code, and software are but some of the crucial elements in data intensive research; yet, these elements are noticeably absent when the research is recorded and preserved in perpetuity by way of a scholarly journal article.

The Nature Publishing Group has brought this point to the public attention in a humorous edi- torial stating that "Nature will no longer accept submissions from humans (Homo sapiens) because the heuristics and biases inherent in human decision-making preclude them from conducting reliable science" :http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v477/n7363/full/477244a.html .
Nanopublications ( http://www.nanopub.org ) have been proposed as a single format for re- search objects [26,27].

Tools for authoring, sharing, interpreting, citing, tracking and prioritizing nanopublications are currently under development as part of the Open PHACTS consor- tium ( http://openphacts.org ), which also provides the rst sandbox environment for scalability and stress tests.

The myExperiment ( http://www.myexperiment.org ) social web site has demonstrated that by adopting content-sharing tools for repositories of workows, we can enable social networking around workows and provide community support for social tagging, comments, ratings and recommenda- tions, social network analysis and reuse mining (what is used with what, for what, and by whom), and mixing of new workows with those previously deposited.
ReaderMeter ( http://readermeter.org/ ) com- putes impact indicators from readership in reference management systems.
For example, in mathematics, the PolyMath project ( http://polymathprojects.org/ ) gathers hundreds of mathematicians throughout the world to work on advanced mathematical proofs on a wiki.

In computer science, many community events such as the TREC information retrieval challenge ( http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text_ Retrieval_Conference ), the trading agent competition ( www.sics.se/tac/ ), and the ontology alignment competition are organized completely online ( http://oaei.ontologymatching.org/ ).

In the Life Sciences, on-line data repositories like UniProt (( www.uniprot.org/ ) are central to the eld, but additionally sites like BioStar ( http://biostar.stackexchange.com/ ) act as a clearing- house for sharing expertise.
